Manuscript metadata collected by Digital Scriptorium from Grolier Club (MS 01)

datavalue.value: Obtained before December 1881 by Hamilton Cole (Grolier member, 1884-89) ; his sale (New York, 7 April 1890 n. 31, pl.), bought by Edward Bement (Grolier member, 1884-1931) who bequeathed it to the Grolier Club in 1932.

Binding: Bound, 1881, in red crushed levant morocco by William Matthews (bookbinder in Brooklyn, NY and Grolier Club member, 1884-96) for Hamilton Cole; covers of both volumes tooled in gilt to the design by Le Gascon on a Plantin bible of the Marquis d'Adda.
Figurative details, ff. 1-303v; ff. 1-351v: 82 historiated initials (with two probably missing on the leaves that would have begun Exodus and Leviticus).
Layout, ff. 1-303v; ff. 1-351v: Gatherings apparently of 24 leaves (the psalter not on a separate quire); 2 columns of 46 lines.

ff. 1-303v; ff. 1-351v: In the usual order for thirteenth century French bibles, and with the usual texts (but adding the prayer of Solomon to the end of Ecclesiasticus, and the Nicene Creed to the end of the Psalms). The expected set of 64 prologues is expanded to 68.

Traces of a library stamp on f. 1. Acquired from Robson and Kerslake (according to de Ricci) by Daniel B. Fearing of Newport, Rhode Island who gave it to the Grolier Club in 1908.
Binding: Bound in modern black morocco with gilt arabesque designs by Riviere and Son, 1889; spine gilt in 6 panels; edges gilt.
Figurative details, ff. 1-154v: 13 half-page miniatures in arched frames.
Layout, ff. 1-154v: 19 gatherings mainly of 8 leaves; 16 long lines (17 long lines in the calendar).

ff. 1-154v: Artist of the Annunciation with some similarties to the Master of Thomas Hoo; secondary artist provisionally named as above from The Hague, Koninklijke Bibliotheek, MS 76 E 18; both artists in the tradition of the Boucicaut Master and the Bedford Master.

ff. 1-154v: Full calendar in French; gospel pericopes; Obsecro te & O intemerata (masc. forms); Hours of the BVM; Penitential psalms & litany; Short hours of the Cross and of the Holy Spirit; Office of the dead; prayers in French (Sonet 458, 504, 1876).
This description is based on the extensive work of Prof. James Marrow.
ff. 1-154v: We thank Prof. James Marrow for naming the artist, and for his collaboration with Francois Avril in identifying parallel manuscripts.

datavalue.value: Incipiunt ethimologie et concordantie conclusionum per reverendissimum dominum magistrum petrum de pergamo

Henry, Prince of Wales (1594-1612); Thomas Watson (1720-79), S. J.;Thomas Pennant (1726-98); by inheritance to Rudolph (1823-92), Earl of Denbigh; Denbigh sale, Christie's, 4-7-1938, lot 12 to Stonehill; Edith Wetmore (1870-1966); in 1955 to Prov.Pub.Lib.

Binding: Gold-stamped calf: in each corner 2 arrows in saltire, points in base, surmounted by a heart and ensigned with a royal crown, within a base of fleur-de-lys and in the flaunches a Tudor rose; center stamp of feathers, enfiled with a crown, w/olive branches.
Figurative details, ff. 1-149v: Innumerable sketched figures that act as a rebus-like mnemonic device, with the same figure reoccuring at need.

Layout, ff. 1-149v: Bible usually in 10 compartments to a page: 3 rectangular shapes each in upper & lower registers ; 4 in the middle register but in triangular shapes formed by a V (itself dimidiated) placed over the entire middle register.
Manuscript note: It is said that the book had been a gift from Elizabeth of Bohemia (1596-1662), daughter of James I of England, to her brother, Henry. Former call number: C091 B582b.

Bibliography: Susanne Rischpler, Biblia Sacra figuris expressa: Mnemotechnische Bilderbibln des 15. Jahrhunderts(Wiesbaden 2001), discussing the five known mss of this type; the Providence book is described on pp. 187-190; meanings of the symbols are on pp. 171-181.
ff. 1-149v: Foliated in modern pencil in lower right corner of recto. In the center lower margins of ff. 7, 15, 25, 35, 45, 55, 64, 76 are red roman numerals (I - VIII) that may be quire numbers.

ff. i-iii verso + 1-3; ff. 3v-5v blank: Doctoris angelici divi Thomæ Aquinatis Opera omniaed. By Stanislas Edouard Frette' and Paul Mare' (Paris, 1871-1880) vols. 34-35; here copied sparsim throughout the book, and to be read in this order: ff. 130-138v, 119-128v, 1-3, 140-147v, 129.
f. 6: Text is divided into seven points, and is complete on this page.

ff. 6v-7: Groupings of the O.T. books of the bible into Legal, Historical, Sapiential, Prophetic; then the N.T. in the Gospels, the Catholic Epistles, the Pauline Epistles (this list carried forward by a tie mark, "f," from the lower verso to the recto).

ff. 87-100: This text also in Vienna, Osterreichische Nationalbibliothek, Cod. 505, ff. 3-11v, containing the series of O.T. patriarchs from Adam to Christ. Each genealogical line follows a specific colored line: red, blue, light purple and so on.
Explicit, ff. 87-100: Considerans sacre historie prolixitatem.

ff. 100-110v: Sequence of Roman emperors and German and Bohemian kings along a green line, beginning with Claudius and ending with Frederick III of Hapsburg who reigned 1452-1493; his accession date provides a possible terminus post quem for the copying of the ms.
f. 111v; ff. 112-116v blank: Sketch of two heads, possibly later in date, on otherwise blank leaves.
ff. 117-118v: Materials relevant to the Dominicans for preaching. The Conclusionesare copied at two points throughout the book and should be read ff. 117-118v, 148r.

ff. 119-128v: Doctoris angelici divi Thomæ Aquinatis Opera omniaed. By Stanislas Edouard Frette' and Paul Mare' (Paris, 1871-1880) vols. 34-35; here copied sparsim throughout the book, and to be read in this order: ff. 130-138v, 119-128v, 1-3, 140-147v, 129.

f. 129r-v: Doctoris angelici divi Thomæ Aquinatis Opera omniaed. By Stanislas Edouard Frette' and Paul Mare' (Paris, 1871-1880) vols. 34-35; here copied sparsim throughout the book, and to be read in this order: ff. 130-138v, 119-128v, 1-3, 140-147v, 129.

ff. 130-138v: Doctoris angelici divi Thomæ Aquinatis Opera omniaed. By Stanislas Edouard Frette' and Paul Mare' (Paris, 1871-1880) vols. 34-35; here copied sparsim throughout the book, and to be read in this order: ff. 130-138v, 119-128v, 1-3, 140-147v, 129.

f. 139v: S. Rischpler suggests that this list was added to the book while in the possession of Henry, Prince of Wales (d. 1612), although the hand does not look English, and the list only need have been added after the accession of Rudolph II in 1576.

ff. 140-147v: Doctoris angelici divi Thomæ Aquinatis Opera omniaed. By Stanislas Edouard Frette' and Paul Mare' (Paris, 1871-1880) vols. 34-35; here copied sparsim throughout the book, and to be read in this order: ff. 130-138v, 119-128v, 1-3, 140-147v, 129.
f. 148; f. 148v blank: Materials relevant to the Dominicans for preaching. The Conclusionesare copied at two points throughout the book and should be read ff. 117-118v, 148r.
f. 149; f. 149v blank: Prayers based on the psalm, Levavi oculos meos.

datavalue.value: Carthusians of Buxheim; Hugo, Graf von Waldbott-Bassenhim (his sale, Munich, 20 September 1883, lot 2672); Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of San Francisco.
Binding: Bound in stamped leather overs wooden boards with 2 fore edge brass clasps; some gilt tooling.; 15 fore edge tabs to mark major text divisions.
Script, ff. 1-78v: Liturgical gothic book hand.
Layout, ff. 1-78v: Gatherings of 8, catchwords present, quire and leaf signatures in letter of the alphabet and roman numeral (out of order in 7th quire); 18 long lines of text.

Bibliography: Possibly to be identified with the manuscript described by De Ricci on p. 26 at n. 1 (but wrong text ?, wrong number of leaves, and wrong lot number in Waldbott-Bassenheim sale, which De Ricci says was 2640).
ff. 1-78v: On ff. 1-46v, psalter; ff. 46v-58, hymns; ff. 58-78v, office for the dead.
This description provided by D. J. Dutschke and C. W. Dutschke.

datavalue.value: Incipit epistola Petri Damiani de die iudicii

On f. 1, illegilbe even under ultra-violet light due to stain, "Iste liber est monachorum <?> deputatus monasterii <sancte Marie ?> <?>." On f. i verso in a modern Italian hand, "14.6.13" written over "A.42000." Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of S. F.
Binding: Bound, s. XIX with labels on spine, "Paschasii De corpore et sanguine Domini" and "Bertoni opera."
ff. 39-135: Terminus post quem provided by texts: f. 132, death note of Bonaventura Bertoni in 1719; ff. 133-134, speech by Pope Innocent in 1666 and a rhyme in Italian of an event in 1686.
ff. 1-36: On f. 1, Regis adire sacre qui vis sollemnia mense . . . (15 verses spelling "Radbertus levita"); ff. 1-2, dedicatory letter.
Explicit, ff. 1-36: Quisquis catholicorum recte dominum cuncta creasse de nichilo.
Explicit, ff. 36-38v: Dilectissimo fratri Ade Petrus peccator monachus humilis in domino salutem. Quod me, frater karissime, quid ante mundi creationem fuerit . . .

ff. 39-135: ff. 39-45v, life of St. Maurus by Maurus Verdoni; ff. 47-111v, sermons in Italian; f. 112v, list of schismatic Greeks; ff. 113-114v, Memorialein first person, signed J. Bonaventura Cesenas Capuccinus; ff. 115-132, Elucidationesagainst Calvinists.
This description provided by D. J. Dutschke and C. W. Dutschke.

datavalue.value: Book of Hours, use of Rome

On ff. 105v, 109v-141v, in margins, notes of the Floriani family, 1591-1702, in areas near Bologna (S. Martino in Argile, S. Lorenzo del Castello di Budrio, Dozza; Budrio); Adolph Sutro (1830-1898), mayor of San Francisco.

Binding: Bound, s. XVII, in leather over pasteboards, blind stamped with a rosette surrounding the IHS monogram; evidence of 2 fore edge clasps closing from top to bottom; 3 fore edge tabs; on the front pastedown, a woodcut of the Crucifixion.
Figurative details, ff. 1-172v: Four historiated initials.
Script, ff. 1-172v: Rounded gothic book hand.
Layout, ff. 1-172v: Gatherings of 10 leaves, except for the 11th (of 8) and the last two (of 2, counting pastedown); 14 long lines ruled in ink.

ff. 1-172v: ff. i-iii verso, additions; ff. 1-79, Hours of the BVM; ff. 79v-80v, added prayers; ff. 81-105v, Penitential psalms & litany; ff. 106-108v, rhyming prayer in Italian; ff. 109-165, Office of the Dead; ff. 166-169v, Office of the Cross; ff. 170-172v, added.
This description provided by D. J. Dutschke and C. W. Dutschke.
